Both parties in either kind of adoption must be cives, and the adopter‚ of course, must be sui iuris. ln the parallel passage of Gaius (i. 98, 99) adrogation is said to take place populi auctoritate, and the term is ex- plained : ‘quod et isqui adoptat rogatur, id est, interrogatur an velit eum quem adoptaturus sit iustum sibi filiurn esse, et is qui adoptatur rogatur an id fieri patiatur, et populus rogatur an id fieri iubeat! Adrogation was originally effected, after a preliminary inquiry by the pontifices, in the comitia curiata, by a legislative act of that assembly: subsequently the thirty curiae dwindled down to thirty lictors, who represented the authority of the people‚ and at some time aster Gaius the form was superseded by imperial rescript (‘ perinde valet . . . ac si per populum facta esset ’ Diocletian and Maximian in Cod. 8. 48. 2); instead of the preliminary pontificat inquiry there was an investigation by a magis- trate thereto commissioned by tbe Emperor, of which the main purpose was the protection of the person robe adrogated, especially against the danger of adoption by some one much poorer than himself, whose motive might be mere avarice : ‘adrogationes non temere nec inexplorate com· mittuntur. Nam comitia arbitris pontificibus praebentur, quae curiata appellantur, aetasque eius, qui adrogare vult, an liberis potius gignendis idonea sit, bonaque eius, qui adrogatur, ne insidiose appetita sint, con- sideratur’ Gellius, noct Att. 5. ro: this was particularly the case in the adrogatio of impubes, t 3 inf.
